<HEADLINE>
<P>
VENTURA COUNTY REVIEW: INCENTIVE PROGRAM SPARKS PROFITS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Jack Searles 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Camarillo-based Power-One Inc. tossed an especially green St. Patrick's Day 
party last week for its 200 Ventura County employees. 
</P>
<P>
 As a reward for a successful year, the company paid out $342,000 in bonuses -- 
an average of $1,700 per person. That brings the bonuses received worldwide 
this year by Power-One's employees to $500,000. 
</P>
<P>
 "It was the first year of our new incentive program, and we're very pleased 
with the way it's worked out," says Steve Goldman, Power-One's president and 
chief executive. "We announced specific goals, and everyone rallied to reach 
them. It's only appropriate that the rewards should be shared with the 
employees." 
</P>
<P>
 Power-One is a privately held company that produces power equipment for the 
industrial, telecommunications, data-processing and medical markets. 
</P>
<P>
 Since an incentive program was introduced in January, 1993, employees have 
responded by improving product quality, cutting costs and speeding up the 
introduction of new products, Goldman reported. 
</P>
<P>
 In contrast to many other California electronics concerns, Power-One showed 
strong increases in sales and profits last year. Goldman gives much of the 
credit for the gains to the new incentive program. Company revenues rose almost 
8%, to $60 million, while profits jumped more than 50%. Goldman declined to 
disclose the profit figure, but said he expects a similar percentage increase 
in earnings and a 15% rise in sales in 1994. 
</P>
<P>
 "We're definitely continuing the incentive program," Goldman said. "Our 
employees say they'll not only reach this year's goals, but that we're going to 
make even greater improvements." 
</P>
<P>
 Power-One this year plans a major upgrading of its 100,000-square-foot plant 
on Calle Plano, including the expansion of an automated sheet-metal shop and 
the addition of new manufacturing equipment. About a dozen new employees will 
be hired in Camarillo this year, mostly skilled sheet-metal workers, Goldman 
said. 
</P>
<P>
 Power-One has a worldwide payroll of about 1,000. In addition to its Camarillo 
headquarters, the company has factories in Mexico and Puerto Rico. 
</P>
</TEXT>
