<HEADLINE>
<P>
EAST VALLEY FOCUS: KIDS' ART CHOSEN FOR CONCERT PROGRAM COVER 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JILL LEOVY 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 It wasn't a job to be envied. 
</P>
<P>
 Intent frowns lingered on the faces of the five judges charged with choosing 
one of 63 children's art projects Monday in Woodland Hills. The artwork they 
sought was to become the face of this season's concerts at Warner Park; it 
would be reproduced on every concert program from June until September. 
</P>
<P>
 And although the volunteer judges were equipped with a strict numerical 
grading system to aid their task, a few seemed weighed down by the 
responsibility. 
</P>
<P>
 "I'm taking this very seriously," said Los Angeles City Councilwoman Laura 
Chick, one of the judges, who kept her pen ready on her clipboard as she made 
her way through the gallery. 
</P>
<P>
 "They are all wonderful," said Wendy Marlett, who was trying to keep in mind 
which would reproduce well in the concert program's black and white. 
</P>
<P>
 The event was the second annual Concerts in the Park poster contest sponsored 
by Valley Cultural Center. Fourth-, fifth- and sixth-graders from area schools 
submitted entries, all built around the theme of "Friends, Family and Music." 
</P>
<P>
 The posters featured stick figures shaped like microphones, animated musical 
instruments, harps, birds and beach blankets. One featured a fluegelhorn, 
complete with caption to identify it.  
</P>
<P>
 But in the end, it was the depiction of two dragons playing saxophones that 
distinguished the winning artwork, rendered by 9-year-old Adrienne 
Herbst-Holmes, a fourth-grader at Woodland Hills Elementary School. Adrienne 
described the dragon theme as one she has been developing over the course of 
several artworks and said she prefers drawing to music. 
</P>
<P>
 Not so for third-place winner Erika Leishman, 9, of the same school. Erika 
said her inspiration for a concert scene was simple and literal: Her parents 
take her to the concerts every summer. 
</P>
<P>
 "I love going," she explained. 
</P>
<P>
 Adrienne will be awarded a $200 savings bond as a prize. Erika will receive a 
$50 savings bond, and second-place winner Evelyn Park of Welby Way Magnet 
School will receive a $100 bond. JILL LEOVY 
</P>
</TEXT>
